<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange_reso=
lvents" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lagrange resolvents">Lagrange resolv=
ents</a></div>
<p>An alternative way of deriving the quadratic formula is via the method o=
f <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange_resolvents" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Lagrange resolvents">Lagrange resolvents</a>,<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-Clark_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Quadratic_formula#cite_note-Clark-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which is an early=
 part of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galois_theory" title=3D"G=
alois theory">Galois theory</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-efei_15-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_formula#cite_not=
e-efei-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
This method can be generalized to give the roots of <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_polynomial" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cubic po=
lynomial">cubic polynomials</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Quartic_polynomial" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quartic polynomial">qu=
artic polynomials</a>, and leads to Galois theory, which allows one to unde=
rstand the solution of algebraic equations of any degree in terms of the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetry_group" title=3D"Symmetry gr=
oup">symmetry group</a> of their roots, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Galois_group" title=3D"Galois group">Galois group</a>.
</p><p>This approach focuses on the roots themselves rather than algebraica=
lly rearranging the original equation. Given a monic quadratic polynomial <=
span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-ele=
ment-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" st=
yle=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" a=
lttext=3D"{\displaystyle \textstyle x^{2}+px+q}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
