<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Historical_development">His=
torical development</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DQuadratic_formula&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit=
 section: Historical development"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The earliest methods for solving quadratic equations were geometric. Bab=
ylonian cuneiform tablets contain problems reducible to solving quadratic e=
quations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEIrving201334_23-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_formula#cite_note-FOOTN=
OTEIrving201334-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Egyptian <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Berlin_Papyrus_6619" title=3D"Berlin Papyrus 6619">Berlin Papyru=
s</a>, dating back to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_K=
ingdom_of_Egypt" title=3D"Middle Kingdom of Egypt">Middle Kingdom</a> (2050=
 BC to 1650 BC), contains the solution to a two-term quadratic equation.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Quadratic_formula#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The Greek mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euc=
lid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a> (circa 300 BC) used geometric methods to s=
olve quadratic equations in Book 2 of his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Elements</a></i=
>, an influential mathematical treatise<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEIrving20=
1339_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qua=
dratic_formula#cite_note-FOOTNOTEIrving201339-25"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Rules for qua=
dratic equations appear in the Chinese <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/The_Nine_Chapters_on_the_Mathematical_Art" title=3D"The Nine Chapte=
rs on the Mathematical Art">The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art</a></=
i> circa 200 BC.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Aitken_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_formula#cite_note-Aitken-26"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESmith1923[httpsarchiveorgdetailshisto=
ryofmathema0001davipage380_p.&amp;nbsp;380]_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_formula#cite_note-FOOTNOTESmi=
th1923[httpsarchiveorgdetailshistoryofmathema0001davipage380_p.&amp;nbsp;38=
0]-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> In his work <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Arithmetica" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Arithmetica">Arithmetica</a></i=
>, the Greek mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophan=
tus" title=3D"Diophantus">Diophantus</a> (circa 250 AD) solved quadratic eq=
uations with a method more recognizably algebraic than the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_algebra" title=3D"Geometric algebra">geo=
metric algebra</a> of Euclid.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEIrving201339_25-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_for=
mula#cite_note-FOOTNOTEIrving201339-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> His solution gives only=
 one root, even when both roots are positive.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESm=
ith1923[httpsarchiveorgdetailshistoryofmathema0001davipage134_p.&amp;nbsp;1=
34]_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quad=
ratic_formula#cite_note-FOOTNOTESmith1923[httpsarchiveorgdetailshistoryofma=
thema0001davipage134_p.&amp;nbsp;134]-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_mathematics" tit=
le=3D"Indian mathematics">Indian mathematician</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Brahmagupta" title=3D"Brahmagupta">Brahmagupta</a> include=
d a generic method for finding one root of a quadratic equation in his trea=
tise <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Br%C4%81hmasphu%E1%B9%ADas=
iddh%C4%81nta" title=3D"Br=C4=81hmasphu=E1=B9=ADasiddh=C4=81nta">Br=C4=81hm=
asphu=E1=B9=ADasiddh=C4=81nta</a></i> (circa 628 AD), written out in words =
in the style of that time.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bradley_29-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_formula#cite_note-B=
radley-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_formula#cite_note-30"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> His solution of the quadratic equation <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<=
span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xml=
ns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \textst=
yle ax^{2}+bx=3Dc}">
  <semantics>
