pedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_formula#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The 9th-century Persian mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Mu%E1%B8%A5ammad_ibn_M%C5%ABs%C4%81_al-Khw%C4%81rizm%C4%AB" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mu=E1=B8=A5ammad ibn M=C5=ABs=C4=81 al-Khw=C4=81=
rizm=C4=AB">Mu=E1=B8=A5ammad ibn M=C5=ABs=C4=81 al-Khw=C4=81rizm=C4=AB</a> =
solved quadratic equations algebraically.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEIrving=
201342_34-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Q=
uadratic_formula#cite_note-FOOTNOTEIrving201342-34"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The quadrat=
ic formula covering all cases was first obtained by <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Stevin" title=3D"Simon Stevin">Simon Stevin</a> in =
1594.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_formula#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 1637 <a href=
